<!-- ═══ NARRATIVE ═══ -->
<section class="sp-narrative">
  <div class="sp-narrative-inner">
    <h2 class="sp-narrative-heading reveal">THE JOURNEY</h2>

    <div class="reveal">
      <p>When I rejoined Brandon Timinsky at ZAR, the product was a mess. A freelancer had left behind chaotic Figma files, inconsistent patterns, and no system to speak of. My first job was to throw it all away and start fresh.</p>

      <p><strong>I built the design system three times.</strong> Techtonic went through three full iterations — not because it failed, but because the product evolved that fast. The final version: 670+ components, 37 Figma pages, 103 icons, 3 platforms (iOS, Android, Web). It's the backbone of everything ZAR ships.</p>

      <p>I led the branding overhaul with Ragged Edge in London — the same agency that rebranded Wise. We rebuilt ZAR's identity from the ground up: visual language, tone, motion, everything. I was the design counterpart on the client side, ensuring every brand decision translated into product reality.</p>

      <p><strong>Service design and on-ground research drove the biggest wins.</strong> The Golden Flow project reduced onboarding from 18 steps to 4 — a 77.8% reduction. This wasn't guesswork. I mapped every touchpoint, identified where users dropped off, and redesigned the flow to match how people actually behave when they first open a financial app in emerging markets.</p>

      <p>Cash QR Consolidation tackled a critical business problem: 72% of transactions were bypassing the order system entirely. Merchants were using personal QR codes instead of business ones. I consolidated the flow so every transaction was tracked, reconciled, and visible — protecting both the user and the business.</p>

      <p>Merchant Onboarding went from 19 steps to 4. Same philosophy: remove everything that doesn't directly serve the user's goal.</p>

      <p><strong>Then I started building AI tools.</strong> Chothu was an AI design consultant I built internally — it could answer design system questions, suggest component usage, and help engineers self-serve without pinging the design team. Engineer Self-Serve Design became a real thing: engineers could ship UI without a designer in the loop for standard patterns.</p>

      <p>MACHINA was the culmination — an internal AI design suite with 5 tools that automated repetitive design work. Content generation, layout suggestions, component mapping, QA checks, documentation. I essentially automated myself out of the job — and that was the point. The best design leaders make themselves unnecessary.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

